{# Introduction Section - Natural, Book-Like Reading Flow #}
<section class="section">
  <div class="content-container">
    <h2 class="section-title">What Is Humanist Modernism?</h2>

    {# Single wider column for natural, book-like reading (max 72ch for optimal comfort) #}
    <div class="max-w-[72ch] mx-auto space-y-6">
      <p class="text-body-xl leading-[1.8] text-text-primary">
        Humanist Modernism emerged as a thoughtful response to the cold precision of early modernist
        design. While honoring the clarity and rational structure of Swiss Design, it prioritizes
        <strong class="text-text-primary font-semibold"
          >human readability, emotional warmth, and cognitive comfort</strong
        >
        above geometric perfection.
      </p>

      <p class="text-body-lg leading-[1.8] text-text-secondary">
        This approach combines the best of two worlds: the systematic thinking and visual order of
        modernism with the accessible, human-centered principles that make design truly serve its
        audience. The result is communication that feels both sophisticated and approachable.
      </p>
    </div>

    {# Blockquote with intentional margin bleed for asymmetric balance #}
    <blockquote class="pull-quote">
      <span class="text-[1.5rem] leading-[1.6] block mb-md"
        >"Design is not just what it looks like and feels like. Design is how it works."</span
      >
      <cite class="quote-attribution">— Steve Jobs</cite>
    </blockquote>
  </div>
</section>

